HIER(7)                    Horus Filesystem Hierarchy                   HIER(7)

NAME
    hier - the layout of the Horus filesystem

DESCRIPTION
    Horus keeps its files in a single encrypted object store served by the
    ring-3 fs_server. The fs_server creates this directory skeleton at boot,
    so a fresh system always shows a real layout rather than an empty root:

    /           The root directory.

    /bin        Executable programs, run by typing their name. The ported GNU
                coreutils (cat, echo, head, wc, seq, printf, tail, ...) live
                here, provisioned from GRUB boot modules. A /bin/<name>
                shadows the shell's lighter builtin of the same name.

    /etc        System configuration. Empty for now.

    /home       Per-user home directories. Empty for now.

    /lib        Shared libraries. Empty for now (programs are static-linked).

    /usr        Read-only user data and programs.

    /usr/share  Architecture-independent data:

    /usr/share/man
                Manual pages, one plain-text file per command (this page is
                /usr/share/man/hier). The man(1) command reads them from here.

NOTES
    Every file is owned by a uid the kernel attests at login, and the
    fs_server enforces POSIX owner/group/other permissions against it. Root
    (uid 0) is the only ambient authority. Files persist across reboot when
    an ATA disk is present; otherwise the store is an ephemeral RAM volume.

SEE ALSO
    ls(1), cat(1), man(1)
